You are debugging a production issue where a Spring Boot application running on JDK 17 with G1GC experiences a gradual Metaspace growth leading to an `OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace` after dynamic plugins are dynamically loaded and unloaded. The dynamic plugin loader uses a custom ClassLoader. Here is the code snippet responsible for executing tasks within the plugin context:

java
@Service
public class PluginExecutor {
    private final Map<String, ClassLoader> pluginRegistry = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
    private static final ThreadLocal<Object> currentPluginConfig = new ThreadLocal<>();

    public void executePluginTask(String pluginId, String className) throws Exception {
        ClassLoader loader = pluginRegistry.computeIfAbsent(pluginId, id -> new CustomPluginClassLoader(id));
        Class<?> clazz = Class.forName(className, true, loader);
        Object instance = clazz.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();

        currentPluginConfig.set(instance);
        clazz.getMethod("execute").invoke(instance);
    }

    public void unloadPlugin(String pluginId) {
        pluginRegistry.remove(pluginId);
    }
}

You are debugging a production race condition in an inventory management service. The service is a Spring bean containing a stateful instance variable. The class is annotated with Spring's `@Transactional` annotation. During concurrent high-volume requests, inventory counts become inconsistent, and the database shows dirty reads even though the transaction isolation level is set to `Isolation.REPEATABLE_READ`:

java
@Service
public class InventoryService {
    private final InventoryRepository repository;
    private int tempStockAdjustment = 0;

    @Autowired
    public InventoryService(InventoryRepository repository) {
        this.repository = repository;
    }

    @Transactional
    public synchronized void updateStock(Long itemId, int quantity) {
        this.tempStockAdjustment += quantity;
        Inventory inventory = repository.findById(itemId).orElseThrow();
        inventory.setQuantity(inventory.getQuantity() + tempStockAdjustment);
        repository.save(inventory);
        this.tempStockAdjustment = 0;
    }
}
